{"id":"1903.06172","submitter":"Mattia Carlo Sormani","authors":"Emanuele Sobacchi and Mattia Sormani","title":"The effect of rotation on the thermal instability of stratified galactic\n  atmospheres - I. Local analysis","comments":"Accepted for publication in MNRAS. Animations of all the simulations\n  in the paper can be downloaded at the following url:\n  https://www.ita.uni-heidelberg.de/~mattia/download/therm/paper_I.zip","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1093/mnras/stz792","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.GA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Observations show that (i) multiple gas phases can coexist in the atmospheres\nof galaxies and clusters; (ii) these atmospheres may be significantly rotating\nin the inner parts, with typical velocities that approach or even exceed the\nlocal sound speed. The thermal instability is a natural candidate to explain\nthe formation of cold structures via condensation of a hotter gas phase. Here\nwe systematically study the effect of rotation on the thermal stability of\nstratified plane-parallel atmospheres, using both analytical arguments and\nnumerical simulations. We find that the formation of cold structures starting\nfrom small isobaric perturbations is enhanced in the regions where the rotation\nof the system is dynamically important (i.e. when the rotational velocity\nbecomes comparable to the sound speed). In particular, the threshold value of\nthe ratio between the cooling and dynamical time $t_{\\rm cool}/t_{\\rm dyn}$\nbelow which condensations can form is increased by a factor up to $\\sim 10$ in\nthe presence of significant rotation. We briefly discuss the implications of\nour results for galaxies and clusters.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 14 Mar 2019 18:00:01 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-03-27"}
{"id":"1903.06173","submitter":"Shriya Pai","authors":"Shriya Pai and Michael Pretko","title":"Dynamical scar states in driven fracton systems","comments":"This version supersedes all previous versions of this paper","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Lett. 123, 136401 (2019)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.123.136401","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.stat-mech cond-mat.dis-nn cond-mat.str-el quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  One-dimensional fracton systems can exhibit perfect localization, failing to\nreach thermal equilibrium under arbitrary local unitary time evolution. We\ninvestigate how this nonergodic behavior manifests in the dynamics of a driven\nfracton system, specifically a one-dimensional Floquet quantum circuit model\nfeaturing conservation of a U(1) charge and its dipole moment. For a typical\nbasis of initial conditions, a majority of states heat up to a thermal state at\nnear-infinite temperature. In contrast, a small number of states flow to a\nlocalized steady state under the Floquet time evolution. We refer to these\nathermal steady states as ``dynamical scars,\" in analogy with the scar states\nobserved in the spectra of certain many-body Hamiltonians. Despite their small\nnumber, these dynamical scars are experimentally relevant due to their high\noverlap with easily-prepared product states. Each scar state displays a single\nagglomerated fracton peak, in agreement with the steady-state configurations of\nfractonic random circuits. The details of these scars are insensitive to the\nprecise form of the Floquet operator, which is constructed from random unitary\nmatrices. Rather, dynamical scar states arise directly from fracton\nconservation laws, providing a concrete mechanism for the appearance of scars\nin systems with constrained quantum dynamics.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 14 Mar 2019 18:00:01 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 30 Mar 2019 23:54:14 GMT"},{"version":"v3",