{"id":"1903.06608","submitter":"D\\'aniel Kor\\'andi","authors":"D\\'aniel Kor\\'andi, J\\'anos Pach, Istv\\'an Tomon","title":"Large homogeneous submatrices","comments":"21 pages, 2 figures. Revised version, a tabular overview of results\n  added at the end","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A matrix is homogeneous if all of its entries are equal. Let $P$ be a\n$2\\times 2$ zero-one matrix that is not homogeneous. We prove that if an\n$n\\times n$ zero-one matrix $A$ does not contain $P$ as a submatrix, then $A$\nhas an $cn\\times cn$ homogeneous submatrix for a suitable constant $c>0$. We\nfurther provide an almost complete characterization of the matrices $P$\n(missing only finitely many cases) such that forbidding $P$ in $A$ guarantees\nan $n^{1-o(1)}\\times n^{1-o(1)}$ homogeneous submatrix. We apply our results to\nchordal bipartite graphs, totally balanced matrices, halfplane-arrangements and\nstring graphs.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 15 Mar 2019 15:46:15 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 29 Mar 2019 13:37:00 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 12 Oct 2020 17:38:05 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-10-13"}
